#
# Real HTTP security headers for Phantom Lock.
#
# Vite copies `public/` verbatim to the output root, so this lands at
# `dist/_headers` — exactly where Netlify and Cloudflare Pages look for it.
# Other hosts need their own mechanism; the same values live in `vercel.json`
# and in `src/security-headers.ts`, which is the source of truth. A test
# (`src/__tests__/security-headers.test.ts`) fails if these three drift apart.
#
# Why this file exists at all when the build already injects a `<meta>` CSP:
# `frame-ancestors` is IGNORED in a meta policy (W3C CSP Level 3 §3.3), so
# clickjacking protection can only be delivered as a real header.
#
# Note for GitHub Pages: its default Jekyll processing excludes files beginning
# with `_`, so `dist/_headers` is not published there. Harmless (Pages ignores
# the contents anyway), but do not go looking for a missing file.
#
/*
  Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'none'; script-src 'self'; style-src 'self'; img-src 'self' data: blob:; font-src 'self'; connect-src 'none'; worker-src 'none'; child-src 'none'; frame-src 'none'; object-src 'none'; media-src 'none'; manifest-src 'none'; base-uri 'none'; form-action 'self'; frame-ancestors 'none'
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
  X-Frame-Options: DENY
  Referrer-Policy: no-referrer
  Permissions-Policy: camera=(), microphone=(), geolocation=()
